Text: The last few weeks have been an interesting experience.
I am glad that I took a risk and chosen a project that was out of my scope in an attempt to broaden my skills and expose me to a different area of tech.

Although, this project was not as smooth sailing as I had hoped it was fun and there were definitely a couple of take-home, self improvement messages that I need to keep in mind for my next studio project.
The first is to not be afraid to be adventurous.
We decided to keep our project pretty straightforward because we needed to start producing results.
This was okay because this first project, for me, had essentially been the 'tester', to get an idea of how this project was going to go, how I was going to manage myself and working in a team.
Since we now have this experience, I am going to encourage the next project to be more adventurous.

The personal development aspect from this project is indirect - but I see it as the preparation and conditioningÂ of myself to doing something bigger and more adventurous in the next project - of course, also being realistic.
I think a definite pro is that I had the opportunity to learn HTML/CSS and completing the online Udemy course.
Let's just say that I am equipped with more knowledge of HTML and CSS than before this project - a skill development achievement in itself I think!
Perhaps in the next project I could take the opportunity to utilise it more or make web pages in my own time.
The second, is to be more brave.
Coming into this project, I had the least knowledge in HTML/CSS, general development and web development.
I encouraged Bibi to take the reign, because my thought process was that his experiences would instill confidence within our team and our project.
Bibi did a great job in leading the team, especially with no leadership experiences - however, the lesson here is that confidence starts from within myself.
Something I have found interesting about myself is thatÂ  I am in fact a planner - or require some sort of structure to feel at peace.
This is interesting because I have never found myself to be a 'planner' type of person, because 'old me' was very much an improviser and spontaneous.
Perhaps I have 50/50 in both traits - especially working in a team, it is a bit more challenging.
I'm finding that it's important everyone is on the same page and has a clear agenda to have an effective team.
Although Bibi was the leader, I needed to be a bit more brave in taking the initiative to plan or have notes provided for everyone in our meetings - I just didn't want to step on anyones toes.
I guess, there were times that I felt my ideas were deemed as 'not important' or 'unnecessary' that I thought this would be something that would be a waste of time too.
The next note for myself is to 'just do it' and be brave.
Ultimately, not doing so affects my learning experience.
To conclude, I think the studio projects are a great idea, even with the idea of throwing us into the deep end.
To me, this means opportunity for accelerated evolution within ourselves.
I read somewhere once that discomfort means opportunity for personal growth - so I am grateful to have the opportunity to do this.
Overall, I am satisfied about what I have learnt from the first studio project and for now, I will take note of that and continue to develop from there in my next studio project : )
